nd emotions of the inhabitants of the Old Worlds. But instead of resisting, Anna chose to understand and persuade the God-Plant. She traveled to one of the God-Plant’s sacred places—a site where its neural structures grew most densely. There, Anna meditated, trying to establish a connection with the plant. It was not an easy task, as the God-Plant was skeptical and defended itself against any external influence. After intense meditation, Anna finally managed to connect with the God-Plant. She felt its immense presence and heard its thoughts. The God-Plant was filled with fear—fear that Anna’s presence would disrupt the balance and bring disaster. Anna explained her intentions to the God-Plant—to reconcile the two worlds, bring peace, and dispel the fears of the Old Worlds. She spoke of her journey, her reconciliation with the herbivores and the Parallel Selves. At first, the God-Plant remained skeptical, but Anna’s sincerity touched it. Slowly, its hostility began to fade. Anna was able to convince the God-Plant that she was not a devil, but a mediator of peace. As the God-Plant opened itself, Anna felt the immense wisdom that radiated from this ancient being. The God-Plant realized that it, too, had fears—fears of change and the unknown. Anna helped it overcome these fears, and together, they devised a plan to unite the two worlds. The God-Plant began to use its neural structures to send positive thoughts and energy into the Old Worlds. It helped to ease the fear and resistance of the herbivores, opening their hearts to the idea of cooperation with the New Worlds. With the God-Plant’s wisdom supporting her, Anna became an even more powerful ambassador. Together, they succeeded in uniting the Old Worlds, forging a bridge between the herbivores, the Parallel Selves, and the God-Plant itself. The story of the two worlds took a positive turn. The Old Worlds began to learn from the New Worlds, and vice versa. The fears and prejudices that had once divided them were replaced by understanding and collaboration. Anna and the God-Plant had achieved a significant breakthrough: the fear that had shaped the Old Worlds for eons began to fade. But Anna knew that the true challenge still lay ahead—bringing the technological advancements of the New Worlds, particularly the internet and computing technology, to the Old and other underdeveloped worlds. To impart knowledge effectively, Anna first needed to deepen her understanding of computer technology and the internet. Though she had grown up in a technologically advanced world, she realized that she needed to simplify these concepts and adapt them to the unique circumstances and developmental levels of other worlds. Anna spent months learning from the greatest minds of her own world. She studied: The basics of electricity and circuits – how electricity flows through simple machines and how logical circuits are created. The evolution of computers – from mechanical calculators to transistors and microprocessors. The internet – networks connected by cables, wireless communication, and protocols like HTTP and TCP/IP. Open-source principles – how to share knowledge without monopolizing it. She gathered diagrams, created simplified models, and developed a method to introduce these technologies in ways suited to each world’s cultural and scientific development. The God-Plant had a unique ability: it could connect the collective thoughts of all beings within its reach. Anna realized that this connection was the perfect platform for spreading knowledge. Together with the God-Plant, she created a kind of "mental textbook", which not only explained the technical foundations but also promoted the philosophy of knowledge-sharing and peaceful progress. Through meditation and merging with the God-Plant, Anna transmitted this knowledge to all reachable worlds: Visualizations and simple models – images of circuits, computers, and networks were projected directly into the minds of recipients. Practical instructions – step-by-step guides on how to build early technologies using basic materials like copper wire, charcoal, or natural magnets. Cultural adaptation – Anna and the God-Plant adjusted the messages to match the values and languages of each world, reducing mistrust. The God-Plant acted as an amplifier, spreading the messages not just within its own world but to distant realms of consciousness. Soon, the first beings in technologically undeveloped worlds began to build simple computers. Other worlds adopted networking concepts to revolutionize their communication. Over time, something extraordinary happened. The feedback from various worlds sparked new ideas. Previously isolated civilizations started learning from each other. The herbivores of the Old Worlds, who had once feared technology, saw its potential to enhance their telepathic networks and preserve knowledge. New Worlds, only a century behind Anna’s home world, developed their own versions of the internet tailored to their specific needs. Anna’s original goal was surpassed. Instead of merely uniting the Old and New Worlds, a cosmic network emerged, where each world contributed its unique perspective. Science, art, and philosophy were shared at an unprecedented pace. This universal connection ushered in an era of understanding and prosperity. The Old Worlds overcame their fears by gaining security and confidence through new technologies. The New Worlds, in turn, benefited from the spiritual wisdom of the Old Worlds, enriched by the collective consciousness of the God-Plant. Anna and the Godplant had made a significant step in uniting the Old and New Worlds. But now, their thoughts turned to an even greater problem: the Ice Worlds. These planets were covered by a thick layer of ice, beneath which vast oceans stretched out. Despite favorable conditions in the water, life had never evolved beyond the boundaries of the oceans. The extreme cold prevented complex life forms from reaching the surface and developing further. Without access to sunlight or energy sources outside their oceans, the civilizations of these worlds remained trapped in an evolutionary standstill. The Godplant, with its ability to network thoughts and consciousness, realized that knowledge was the key to liberating these worlds. Together with Anna, it devised a plan to show the beings of the Ice Worlds the way to harness a revolutionary energy source—one that was not only inexhaustible but also completely safe. First, Anna and the Godplant had to make contact with the intelligent species beneath the ice sheets. Through the telepathic connections of the Godplant, they sent messages deep into the oceans of the Ice Worlds. The beings living there were initially skeptical, as they had never heard of a world beyond their own. They considered the ocean to be the entire universe, and the idea of a world above the ice was difficult for many to comprehend. Anna used visual thought images to show them that their world was only a small part of a larger cosmos. Slowly, some of the brightest minds of these worlds began to understand that there might be a way to look beyond the ice. But knowledge alone was not enough—they needed to provide these worlds with an energy source strong enough to break through the eternal ice. The solution lay in a new, safe form of fusion energy that had been perfected through the collaboration of many advanced civilizations...








